=== RAW MODEL ANSWER ===
Answer: Step 1: Perform Williamson ether formation on tyrosol (HO–CH2CH2–C6H4–OH) with 4-phenylbutyl bromide (K2CO3/DMF) to give 2-(4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl)ethanol. | Step 2: Convert the alcohol to the primary halide/leaving-group derivative, e.g. PBr3 (or TsCl then displacement), to obtain 2-(4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl)ethyl bromide. | Step 3: From ethyl N-(diphenylmethylene)glycinate, do sequential enolate alkylations (LDA or NaHMDS): first with 1-bromopropane, then with 2-(4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl)ethyl bromide, giving the α,α-disubstituted imino ester EtO2C–C(Pr)(CH2CH2C6H4O(CH2)4Ph)=NCHPh2. | Step 4: Hydrolyze the imine to the free amine and protect it with Boc2O to form ethyl 2-((tert-butoxycarbonyl)amino)-2-propyl-4-(4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl)butanoate. | Step 5: Reduce the ester selectively to the primary alcohol (LiBH4 or LAH) to reach CCC(CO)(CCc1ccc(OCCCCc2ccccc2)cc1)NC(=O)OC(C)(C)C.

=== NORMALIZED STUDENT ANSWER ===
Step 1: Perform Williamson ether formation on tyrosol (HO–CH2CH2–C6H4–OH) with 4-phenylbutyl bromide (K2CO3/DMF) to give 2-(4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl)ethanol. | Step 2: Convert the alcohol to the primary halide/leaving-group derivative, e.g. PBr3 (or TsCl then displacement), to obtain 2-(4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl)ethyl bromide. | Step 3: From ethyl N-(diphenylmethylene)glycinate, do sequential enolate alkylations (LDA or NaHMDS): first with 1-bromopropane, then with 2-(4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl)ethyl bromide, giving the α,α-disubstituted imino ester EtO2C–C(Pr)(CH2CH2C6H4O(CH2)4Ph)=NCHPh2. | Step 4: Hydrolyze the imine to the free amine and protect it with Boc2O to form ethyl 2-((tert-butoxycarbonyl)amino)-2-propyl-4-(4-(4-phenylbutoxy)phenyl)butanoate. | Step 5: Reduce the ester selectively to the primary alcohol (LiBH4 or LAH) to reach CCC(CO)(CCc1ccc(OCCCCc2ccccc2)cc1)NC(=O)OC(C)(C)C.

